gomodel:SYNGO_4047  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Automated change 2024-03-14: GO:0099059 replaced by GO:0048787" , "Rationale: In the previous CC annotation for mGluR4 (ID 1579) it is described that mGluR4 is highly enriched at active zones (AZs) of membranes from different neuronal layers, but in this new annotation, we provide new data on spatial arrangement and stoichiometry of mGluR4 within these AZs.\n\nIn Fig 1B-D, by direct stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy (dSTORM) we can observe a significant number of mGluR4 localizations within parallel fibers active zones (AZs). Previous to this experiment, stainings with a specific mGluR4 antibody (tested in mGluR4 knockout mice in another publication) and bassoon (scaffold protein useful to mark AZs) were carried out.\n\nIn Fig 2, using dSTORM and Density-based spatial clustering of applications with noise (DBSCAN), it is determined that mGluR4 is organized in small nanoclusters within AZs with a higher density or concentration inside than outside AZs. Moreover, In Fig S2 B-D, it is shown that mGluR4 follows a quite homogenous distribution within the AZs.\n\nIn Fig 3 C-D, we can find that mGluR4s mainly present 2 subunits, it means they appear like a dimer the most of the times. In this case, they used a different model for the experiments, Chinese hamster ovary (CHO) cells transfected with SNAP-tagged mGluR4s and then labeled with Alexa Fluor 647 to be imaged by total internal reflection fluorescence (TIRF) microscopy (Fig 3 A-B).\n\nLastly, this paper establishes that we can approximately find 35 mGluR4 subunits per AZ (data are shown in Figs S4 and S5). In this case, they use the previous named CHO cells and limiting and saturating of mGluR4 primary antibody, and dSTORM imaging to estimate the number of localizations per mGluR4 nanocluster.\n\nNote:\nIn Fig 6, we can observe an illustrative scheme of mGluR4 nanoscale spatial organization within the actives zones of parallel fibers.. Experimental description: Wild-type adult FVB mice were used for the preparation of the mouse cerebellar slices." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2345-393X" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1212-5623" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9888-0928" ;
        dc:date           "2024-03-14" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_4047" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

